<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="LGA Briefing" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the LGA (CYS0025)_x000c_</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="93" height="247" alt="" style="margin-left:496.8pt; margin-top:39.6pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65536" /></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from the LGA (CYS0025)</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:auto" /><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About the Local Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Association</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Local Government Association (LGA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is the national voice of local government.  We work with councils to support, promote and improve local government.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems. The LGA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> covers every p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">art of England and Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, supporting local government as the most efficient and accountable part of the public sector.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In the period of the current Parliament, local government core funding will fall by 43 per cent.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The next two years are therefo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re going to be very tough with 2015/16 a ‘crunch’ year when some councils will be unable to meet their statutory obligations to an acceptable minimum (councils face real terms reductions in core funding of 21 per cent across 2014/15 and 2015/16). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We theref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ore need to find new ways of working to prevent local public services from failing. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government currently projects that road traffic on the local roads network will increase by 41 per cent between 2010 and 2040.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the same time, current evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">indicates that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the recent increase in cycling will be largely reversed unless policies change</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Without a change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how transport policy is funded and decisions are taken, the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suffer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> economically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">traffic is caught </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in congestion, while our ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ad surfaces </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deteriorate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA continues to encourage the Government to </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">implement Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2004, to allow councils to enforce mandatory cycle lanes and moving traffic offences. Giving councils powers under </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Part 6 </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">would make cycling safer</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by preventing motorists driving or parking in cycle lanes and by reducing the numbers of illegal turns and other dangerous actions at key junctions.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils are embarking on a range of initiatives to support cyclists, such as lay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing dedicated cycle paths, installing secure cycle parking in high streets and car parks, and promoting cycling proficiency tests. However, they are struggling to maintain a chronically underfunded road system which, coupled with the recent severe funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cuts from central government, means resources for new cycling initiatives or overhauls of road layout and signage are extremely stretched.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Q: Is cycling safe, particularly in towns and cities?</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The risks of cycling need to be carefully considered. For instance, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any consideration should involve a detailed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> analysis of the causes of recent cycling deaths. Any risk involved in cycling needs to be weighed against the health implications of not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">engaging in exercise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Consideration also needs to be given of the impact of journeys being taken by car or public transport, if they are not taken by bicycle. For example, this could have a knock on effect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in terms of air quality and road safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Encoura</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ging cycling and walking is vital if we are to encourage healthier lifestyles and reduce the strain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the NHS. It is also vital if we are to avoid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gridlock in our towns and cities that could arise if current traffic projections </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">41 per cent increase i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n traffic on local roads by 2040</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">come to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fruition</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The appropriate question is can cycling be made safer, and if so, can that be funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Q: What could central and local government do to improve cycling safety?</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Part 6Traffic Management Act 2004: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Civil en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">forcement of traffic contraventions</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of the quickest and simplest measures the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment could take to improve cycling safety would be to implement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">art 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allow councils outside London to enforce cycle lanes and to enforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">various </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">traffic offences (for example banned turns)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> particular danger to cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The chief issue for councils in requesting these powers is traffic manage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment, which would be enhanced by enforcing banned turns and box junctions. There will be no obligation on councils to adopt these powers and there will be a cost in doing so at any particular location. This will encourage councils to adopt the powers only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where they think they will make a difference to congestion and safety, including that of cyclists. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The enforcement of cycle lanes would help promote cycling and increase safety. In 2011 accidents caused by banned turns or wrong direction driving (one per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cent of all accidents) cost an estimated £83.7m</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA has consistently called for the implementation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">art 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 since that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieved Royal Assent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was passed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 2011 report on congestion by the House of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commons Transport Select Committee argued that ‘Making the most of the road capacity for all road users requires active management of the road network by the highway authorities and they need the appropriate tools to do that…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We can see no reason why Part </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 should not be fully commenced to enable local authorities to deal more effectively with moving traffic contraventions and we recommend that the Government bring this part of the Act into force, by 2013’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Welsh Gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ernment has taken action to implement Part 6 this year and the DfT has been considering submission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the LGA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and from Nottingham and Sheffield councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> demonstrating the benefits of the legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">last December</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#262626; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Road Maintenance</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:'MS Gothic'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Road maintenance is also an issue of concern when it comes to safety. Decades of underfunding, severe winters and widespread flooding has left large swathes of our roads in disrepair, with many councils struggling to move beyond simply patching up a deteri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orating network. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current funding for road maintenance is £829m a year short of the level needed to prevent the 98 per cent of roads maintained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deteriorating further and even if funding was adequate it would take more than a decade to cle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar the backlog of repairs.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Increased highways maintenance funding from 2015 will still leave a shortfall of over half a billion pounds a year. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal government does not have the money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to maintain its highways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">due to the funding cuts it has endured – 43%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> across this current Parliament. We need a radical new solution to ensure a sustainable and reliable model of local government for the future (see funding section at the end of this submission).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transport Devolution</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycling is a great example of the need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for effective transport devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – being both an example of the need to see transport as a whole and of the interaction between transport and other policies.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycling can play a key role in solving transport problems. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At its most dramatic, this can mean</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> motorway congestion is caused by short distance commuter traffic, encouraging cycling and public transport use by commuters may prove cheaper and more effective means of reducing that congestion than widening the motorway.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> But cycling can also b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e part of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> strategy on a smaller scale, opening up access to jobs and services in areas where demand is too </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diffuse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or sporadic to justi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fy a subsidis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed bus service. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cycling is also a vital part of encouraging healthy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">communities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent needs to be able to plan local transport facilities whilst considering other interrelated issues such as health and wellbeing, environment and planning. For example, councils may want to encourage cycling to school and this could influence such diverse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> activities as:</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">planning the location of schools and homes;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designating paths as cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">paths;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivering the curriculum to emphasize the link between cycling and health or to teach cycle safety;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">getting GPs to advise parents about the benefits of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycling with their children to school;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">designing road layout; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">targeting parking enforcement .</span></li></ul></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To be effective, the promotion of cycling needs to go hand in hand with effective traffic management and public transport provision to minimi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e other traffic and ensure it does not deter cyclists. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the same time we need to recognize that places are different, the local geography will have some influence on the popularity of cycling and the needs of rural and urban areas will be different. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cling needs to be promoted in a way that is locally relevant.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the absence of effective devolution, the DfT’s National Traffic Model predicts that while cycle use will rise from 2.9</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">illio</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n miles in 2010 to 3.4</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">illion</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> miles in 2015, it will fall back to almost the 2010 level by 2025 with subsequent growth at such a low level it represents a decline relative to population, assuming that current policy remains unchanged. This suggests that the </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment will fail to mee</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t its existing cycling targets. While this is only a projection based on the continuation of existing policy</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is a danger that it becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy with projected low use justifying a decline in funding. Experience in London (where c</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar traffic reduced five times as much between 2003 and 2010 as DfT had predicted) shows that where local government has the power and funding to manage traffic effectively and provide alternatives, projected traffic growth does not have to be a self-fulfil</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ling prophecy.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils need to be given greater local control over how money is spent, based on place and need</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This will allow them to take a holistic approach to transport in their area, including all the different elements such as rail, roads, buses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, cycling etc. This would also help address the problems with transport funding. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Leadership, commitment and capacity in local government</span><span style="font-family:'MS Gothic'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Up and down the country councils have embarked on a huge range of initiatives to support cyclists, such as:</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">laying </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dedicated and on-road cycle paths;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">installing secure cycle parking in high streets and car parks;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organising community cycle rides; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supporting town centre bike rental schemes; and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; orphans:0; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">promoting cycling proficiency tests and bike safety awareness campaigns.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA would be willing to source specific examples should that be of interest to the Committee. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, councils have been maintaining a chronically underfunded road system for many years which, coupled with severe funding cuts from central government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, means resources for new cycling initiatives or overhauls of road layout and signage are extremely stretched in many areas at the moment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils work with schools and other groups to provide cycling proficiency schemes. However, some councils find the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requirements of the top down government init</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iatives like Bikeability too pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scriptive and bureaucratic for their needs, opting instead for local alternatives which better suit their communities.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Local Sustainable Transport Fund has funded a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycling initiatives. This is being subsumed into the Local Growth Fund from 2015 and it remains to be seen whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycling will continue to receive funding under the new arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="color:#343434; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The financial reality</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the period of the current Parliament, local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government’s core funding will fall by 43 per cent.  At the same time funding pressures are increasing due to our ageing population pushing up demand for adult social care services such as home care for the elderly and infirm, the number of children in car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e doubling and waste </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">management costs rising. LGA analysis shows that these three areas of spending will soak up an ever-larger share of council budgets. Other services – transport, leisure, culture, planning and economic development – will need to accommo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">date the further cuts meaning that spending in these areas will fall by 2019-20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. There will be a funding gap of £15.6 billion by 2020. LGA analysis modelling the future of local government finance revealed that the financial black</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hole facing local governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ent is widening by £2.1 billion per year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   To give local authorities greater financial stability, the LGA issued a submission to HM Treasury ahead of the Autumn Statement calling for the Government:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Avoid making further cuts or topslices </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent funding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To reduce the excessive level of holdbacks in 2015/16.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local government to retain the full growth in the share of business rates.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local discretion over fees and charges.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Publish the Department for Communities and Local Government modelling of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the impact on local services of the funding reductions set out in the 2014/15 and 2015/16 local government finance settlement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To review the handling of future local government settlements so as to rebuild trust and transparency in the system.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whitehall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must consider radical new approaches</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the way local government is funded and give greater control to councils so that spend can be based on local need.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Q: Would it be desirable and feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users, including, for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">example, by prohibiting HGVs from entering city centres at peak hours?</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is a decision that councils should be free to take at a local level. Every area is different, with individual characteristics and circumstances that need to be considered. Central</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> government is not in a position to make such local-based decisions. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/212474/road-transport-forecasts-2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploa</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">ds/attachment_data/file/212474/road-transport-forecasts-2013.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, Table 1. These figures – and all other references to future estimates in this paper, refer to the central case. This is the DfT’s projection of what will happen if existing policies are p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">ursued and the drivers of traffic levels (GDP per capita, population and oil price) follow the central path of  their projected increase.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">See </span><a href="http://www.ctc.org.uk/blog/chris-peck/government-predicts-cycling-will-fall-2040"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ctc.org.uk/blog/chris-peck/government-predicts-cycling-will-fall-2040</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> DfT statistics</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> for 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (</span><a href="http://tinyurl.com/oo3oqr4"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">h